Package: evmr
Type: Package
Title: Extreme Value Modeling for R-Largest Order Statistics
Version: 0.0.0.9000
Authors@R:
    c(
      person("Yire", "Shin", email = "your_email@example.com", role = c("aut", "cre")),
      person("Jeong-Soo", "Park", role = "aut")
    )
Description: Provides tools for extreme value modeling based on
    r-largest order statistics. The package implements parameter
    estimation, return level estimation, profile likelihood-based
    confidence intervals, random generation, and entropy difference
    tests for selecting the number of order statistics r. Several
    r-largest order statistics models are supported, including the
    four-parameter kappa (rK4D), generalized logistic (rGLO),
    generalized Gumbel (rGGD), logistic (rLD), and Gumbel (rGD)
    distributions. The rK4D methodology is described in Shin et al.
    (2022) <doi:10.1016/j.wace.2022.100533>. The rGLO model is
    described in Shin and Park (2024)
    <doi:10.1007/s00477-023-02642-7>, and the rGGD model is described
    in Shin and Park (2025)
    <doi:10.1038/s41598-024-83273-y>. The underlying kappa
    distribution is based on Hosking (1994)
    <doi:10.1017/CBO9780511529443>, the generalized logistic
    distribution relates to Ahmad et al. (1988)
    <doi:10.1016/0022-1694(88)90015-7>, and the generalized Gumbel
    distribution is related to Jeong et al. (2014)
    <doi:10.1007/s00477-014-0865-8>. Penalized likelihood methods for
    extreme value estimation follow Martins and Stedinger (2000)
    <doi:10.1029/1999WR900330> and Coles and Dixon (1999)
    <doi:10.1023/A:1009905222644>. The selection of r is supported
    using methods discussed in Bader et al. (2017)
    <doi:10.1007/s11222-016-9697-3>. The package is designed for
    hydrological, climatological, and environmental extreme value
    analysis.
